Parses `.steno` source text into `Vec<Entry>`: alternating fenced blocks (stroke definitions) and `@`-directive lines that annotate the entry immediately above them. This is the front end of the steno crate's compiler pipeline — its output feeds whatever consumes `Entry`/`EntryFlags` (defined in the parent `parse` module) downstream.

Fence detection (`fence_stroke`) requires **4 or more** backticks, not the usual 3 — a 3-backtick line is treated as stray text and errors out. An opening fence carries the stroke text after the backticks (e.g. `` ````HR/HROU ``); a closing fence has nothing after the ticks. Strokes are split on `/`, trimmed, and empty segments dropped, so `stroke` (`Vec<String>`) can end up shorter than a naive split of `stroke_raw`.

Directives (`@count`, `@arity`, or boolean flags) apply only to `entries.last_mut()` — a directive appearing before any fenced block is a hard error ("directive before any entry"), and directive lines are otherwise indistinguishable from stray text except for the leading `@`. Blank lines, `//`, and `#`-prefixed lines are silently skipped everywhere outside fenced blocks; anything else non-fence, non-directive is rejected as "unexpected text". Unknown directive names fall through to `EntryFlags::set_named(flag)` — that method (in the `parse` module, not this file) is the single source of truth for which boolean flag names are valid, so adding a new flag means editing it there, not here.

Line numbers throughout are 1-based (`i.saturating_add(1)`), and errors always carry the line of the fence-open or directive, not the block's internal line — template-parse errors are reported from `line_no + 1` (the line after the opening fence) since `parse_template` is given that as its base. All arithmetic on indices uses `saturating_add` rather than `+`, so no panics on line-count edge cases even in pathological inputs.

Key entry point: `pub fn parse_source(src: &str) -> Result<Vec<Entry>, StenoError>`. Everything else (`fence_stroke`, `parse_plain_line`, `block_text`, `parse_block`, `directive_parts`, `parse_arity`, `apply_directive`) is private and file-local. `parse_template` (from `super::template`) is the only external parsing dependency, invoked once per block with the joined block body and the computed starting line number.